   COMMENT ON COLUMN "AUTOHAUL"."EWMS_COMPONENTTYPES"."COMPONENTTYPEID" IS 'A globally unique identifier suitable for use in an occasionally connected distributed system as well as a local database.';
   COMMENT ON COLUMN "AUTOHAUL"."EWMS_COMPONENTTYPES"."NAME" IS 'The name of this asset type e.g. Locomotive, Sub-system, Wayside, AutoHaul system etc.';
   COMMENT ON COLUMN "AUTOHAUL"."EWMS_COMPONENTTYPES"."SINGULARWITHINASSET" IS 'Defines whether asset type is required to have one and only one asset within its composite type. An example of a singular asset type is the "DIVA" subsystem which should exist once within a Locomotive asset. An example a non-singular asset type is a Locomotive which will occur multiple times within the "AutoHaul System" Asset type.';
   COMMENT ON COLUMN "AUTOHAUL"."EWMS_COMPONENTTYPES"."COMPONENTCLASS" IS 'The mechanism needed to install or replace this asset type.';
   COMMENT ON COLUMN "AUTOHAUL"."EWMS_COMPONENTTYPES"."STRUCTUREID" IS 'This is also known as AssetID and extracted from the Master Configuration Items.';
   COMMENT ON TABLE "AUTOHAUL"."EWMS_COMPONENTTYPES"  IS 'The definition of the structure of an Asset type within the system. Asset instances can be a definition of a single asset or a hierarchy of components that are in turn assets. Asset structures are defined flexibly at runtime in a database and are not hard coded programmatic structures. There is an advantage to defining re-usable structures/types of assets which have an identical asset hierarchy. An example of an asset type is a Locomotive which is made up of a pre-defined set of sub-systems which in turn contain hardware assets (LRUs) and software module assets. The asset structure defines the structural hierarchy of components that an asset of that structural type has within the broader system.';
